# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: application-sandboxing
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:application-sandboxing/address-space-layout-randomization] The Linux PaX project first coined the term "ASLR", and published the first design and implementation of ASLR in July 2001 as a patch for the Linux kernel.
[src:application-sandboxing/address-space-layout-randomization] It is seen as a complete implementation, providing a patch for kernel stack randomization since October 2002.
[src:application-sandboxing/address-space-layout-randomization] The first mainstream operating system to support ASLR by default was OpenBSD version 3.4 in 2003, followed by Linux in 2005.
[src:application-sandboxing/address-space-layout-randomization] Address space randomization hinders some types of security attacks by making it more difficult for an attacker to predict target addresses.
[src:application-sandboxing/address-space-layout-randomization] For example, attackers trying to execute return-to-libc attacks must locate the code to be executed, while other attackers trying to execute shellcode injected on the stack have to find the stack first.
[src:application-sandboxing/address-space-layout-randomization] In both cases, the system makes related memory-addresses unpredictable from the attackers' point of view.
[src:application-sandboxing/address-space-layout-randomization] These values have to be guessed, and a mistaken guess is not usually recoverable due to the application crashing.
[src:application-sandboxing/address-space-layout-randomization] Address space layout randomization is based upon the low chance of an attacker guessing the locations of randomly placed areas.
[src:application-sandboxing/address-space-layout-randomization] Security is increased by increasing the search space.
[src:application-sandboxing/address-space-layout-randomization] Thus, address space randomization is more effective when more entropy is present in the random offsets.
[src:application-sandboxing/address-space-layout-randomization] Entropy is increased by either raising the amount of virtual memory area space over which the randomization occurs or reducing the period over which the randomization occurs.
[src:application-sandboxing/address-space-layout-randomization] The period is typically implemented as small as possible, so most systems must increase VMA space randomization.
[src:application-sandboxing/address-space-layout-randomization] To defeat the randomization, attackers must successfully guess the positions of all areas they wish to attack.
[src:application-sandboxing/address-space-layout-randomization] For data areas such as stack and heap, where custom code or useful data can be loaded, more than one state can be attacked by using NOP slides for code or repeated copies of data.
[src:application-sandboxing/address-space-layout-randomization] This allows an attack to succeed if the area is randomized to one of a handful of values.
[src:application-sandboxing/address-space-layout-randomization] In contrast, code areas such as library base and main executable need to be discovered exactly.
[src:application-sandboxing/address-space-layout-randomization] Often these areas are mixed, for example stack frames are injected onto the stack and a library is returned into.
[src:application-sandboxing/address-space-layout-randomization] To calculate the probability of an attacker succeeding, a number of attempts α carried out without being interrupted by a signature-based IPS, law enforcement, or other factor must be assumed; in the case of brute forcing, the daemon cannot be restarted.
[src:application-sandboxing/address-space-layout-randomization] The number of relevant bits and how many are being attacked in each attempt must also be calculated, leaving however many bits the attacker has to defeat.
[src:application-sandboxing/address-space-layout-randomization] The following formulas represent the probability of success for a given set of α attempts on N bits of entropy.
[src:application-sandboxing/address-space-layout-randomization] In many systems, $2^{N}$ can be in the thousands or millions.
[src:application-sandboxing/address-space-layout-randomization] On 32-bit systems, a typical amount of entropy *N* is 8 bits.
[src:application-sandboxing/address-space-layout-randomization] For 2004 computer speeds, Shacham and co-workers state "...
[src:application-sandboxing/address-space-layout-randomization] 16 bits of address randomization can be defeated by a brute force attack within minutes." (The authors' statement depends on the ability to attack the same application multiple times without any delay.
[src:application-sandboxing/address-space-layout-randomization] Proper implementations of ASLR, like that included in grsecurity, provide several methods to make such brute force attacks infeasible.
[src:application-sandboxing/address-space-layout-randomization] One method involves preventing an executable from executing for a configurable amount of time if it has crashed a certain number of times.) On modern 64-bit systems, these numbers typically reach the millions at least.
[src:application-sandboxing/address-space-layout-randomization] Android, and possibly other systems, implement *Library Load Order Randomization*, a form of ASLR which randomizes the order in which libraries are loaded.
[src:application-sandboxing/address-space-layout-randomization] An approximation of the number of bits of entropy supplied per needed library appears below; this does not yet account for varied library sizes, so the actual entropy gained is really somewhat higher.
[src:application-sandboxing/address-space-layout-randomization] Attackers usually need only one library; the math is more complex with multiple libraries, and shown below as well.
[src:application-sandboxing/address-space-layout-randomization] The case of an attacker using only one library is a simplification of the more complex formula for $l=1$ .
[src:application-sandboxing/address-space-layout-randomization] These values tend to be low even for large values of l, most importantly since attackers typically can use only the C standard library and thus one can often assume that $\beta \,=1$ .
[src:application-sandboxing/address-space-layout-randomization] However, even for a small number of libraries there are a few bits of entropy gained here; it is thus potentially interesting to combine library load order randomization with VMA address randomization to gain a few extra bits of entropy.
[src:application-sandboxing/address-space-layout-randomization] These extra bits of entropy will not apply to other mmap() segments, only libraries.
[src:application-sandboxing/address-space-layout-randomization] Attackers may make use of several methods to reduce the entropy present in a randomized address space, ranging from simple information leaks to attacking multiple bits of entropy per attack (such as by heap spraying).
[src:application-sandboxing/address-space-layout-randomization] There is little that can be done about this.
[src:application-sandboxing/address-space-layout-randomization] It is possible to leak information about memory layout using format string vulnerabilities.
[src:application-sandboxing/address-space-layout-randomization] Format string functions such as printf use a variable argument list to do their job; format specifiers describe what the argument list looks like.
[src:application-sandboxing/address-space-layout-randomization] Because of the way arguments are typically passed, each format specifier moves closer to the top of the stack frame.
[src:application-sandboxing/address-space-layout-randomization] Eventually, the return pointer and stack frame pointer can be extracted, revealing the address of a vulnerable library and the address of a known stack frame; this can eliminate library and stack randomization as an obstacle to an attacker.
[src:application-sandboxing/address-space-layout-randomization] One can also decrease entropy in the stack or heap.
[src:application-sandboxing/address-space-layout-randomization] The stack typically must be aligned to 16 bytes, and so this is the smallest possible randomization interval; while the heap must be page-aligned, typically 4096 bytes.
[src:application-sandboxing/address-space-layout-randomization] When attempting an attack, it is possible to align duplicate attacks with these intervals; a NOP slide may be used with shellcode injection, and the string '`/bin/sh`' can be replaced with '`////////bin/sh`' for an arbitrary number of slashes when attempting to return to *system*.
[src:application-sandboxing/address-space-layout-randomization] The number of bits removed is exactly $\log _{2}\!\left(n\right)$ for n intervals attacked.
[src:application-sandboxing/address-space-layout-randomization] Such decreases are limited due to the amount of data in the stack or heap.
[src:application-sandboxing/address-space-layout-randomization] The stack, for example, is typically limited to 8 MB and grows to much less; this allows for at most 19 bits, although a more conservative estimate would be around 8–10 bits corresponding to 4–16 KB of stack stuffing.
[src:application-sandboxing/address-space-layout-randomization] The heap on the other hand is limited by the behavior of the memory allocator; in the case of glibc, allocations above 128 KB are created using mmap, limiting attackers to 5 bits of reduction.
[src:application-sandboxing/address-space-layout-randomization] This is also a limiting factor when brute forcing; although the number of attacks to perform can be reduced, the size of the attacks is increased enough that the behavior could in some circumstances become apparent to intrusion detection systems.
[src:application-sandboxing/address-space-layout-randomization] ASLR-protected addresses can be leaked by various side channels, removing mitigation utility.
[src:application-sandboxing/address-space-layout-randomization] Recent attacks have used information leaked by the CPU branch target predictor buffer (BTB) or memory management unit (MMU) walking page tables.
[src:application-sandboxing/address-space-layout-randomization] It is not clear if this class of ASLR attack can be mitigated.
[src:application-sandboxing/address-space-layout-randomization] If they cannot, the benefit of ASLR is reduced or eliminated.
[src:application-sandboxing/address-space-layout-randomization] In August 2024 a paper was published with an empirical analysis of major desktop platforms, including Linux, macOS, and Windows, by examining the variability in the placement of memory objects across various processes, threads, and system restarts.
[src:application-sandboxing/address-space-layout-randomization] The results show that while some systems as of 2024, like Linux distributions, provide robust randomization, others, like Windows and macOS, often fail to adequately randomize key areas like executable code and libraries.
[src:application-sandboxing/address-space-layout-randomization] Moreover, they found a significant reduction in the entropy of libraries after the Linux 5.18 version and identify correlation paths that an attacker could leverage to reduce exploitation complexity significantly.
[src:application-sandboxing/address-space-layout-randomization] Several mainstream, general-purpose operating systems implement ASLR.
[src:application-sandboxing/address-space-layout-randomization] Android 4.0 Ice Cream Sandwich provides address space layout randomization (ASLR) to help protect system and third-party applications from exploits due to memory-management issues.
[src:application-sandboxing/address-space-layout-randomization] Position-independent executable support was added in Android 4.1.
[src:application-sandboxing/address-space-layout-randomization] Android 5.0 dropped non-PIE support and requires all dynamically linked binaries to be position independent.
[src:application-sandboxing/address-space-layout-randomization] Library load ordering randomization was accepted into the Android open-source project on 26 October 2015, and was included in the Android 7.0 release.
[src:application-sandboxing/address-space-layout-randomization] DragonFly BSD has an implementation of ASLR based upon OpenBSD's model, added in 2010.
[src:application-sandboxing/address-space-layout-randomization] It is off by default, and can be enabled by setting the sysctl vm.randomize_mmap to 1.
[src:application-sandboxing/address-space-layout-randomization] Support for ASLR appeared in FreeBSD 13.0.
[src:application-sandboxing/address-space-layout-randomization] Apple introduced ASLR in iOS 4.3 (released March 2011).
[src:application-sandboxing/address-space-layout-randomization] The randomized kernel base is `0x01000000 + ((1+0xRR) * 0x00200000)`, where `0xRR` is a random byte from SHA1 (random data) generated by iBoot (the 2nd-stage iOS Boot Loader).
[src:application-sandboxing/address-space-layout-randomization] The Linux kernel enabled a weak form of ASLR by default since the kernel version 2.6.12, released in June 2005.
[src:application-sandboxing/address-space-layout-randomization] The PaX and Exec Shield patchsets to the Linux kernel provide more complete implementations.
[src:application-sandboxing/address-space-layout-randomization] The Exec Shield patch for Linux supplies 19 bits of stack entropy on a period of 16 bytes, and 8 bits of mmap base randomization on a period of 1 page of 4096 bytes.
[src:application-sandboxing/address-space-layout-randomization] This places the stack base in an area 8 MB wide containing 524,288 possible positions, and the mmap base in an area 1 MB wide containing 256 possible positions.
[src:application-sandboxing/address-space-layout-randomization] ASLR can be disabled for a specific process by changing its execution domain, using `personality(2)`.
[src:application-sandboxing/address-space-layout-randomization] A number of sysctl options control the behavior of mainline ASLR.
[src:application-sandboxing/address-space-layout-randomization] For example, `kernel.randomize_va_space` controls *what* to randomize; the strongest option is 2.
[src:application-sandboxing/address-space-layout-randomization] `vm.mmap_rnd_bits` controls how many bits to randomize for mmap.
[src:application-sandboxing/address-space-layout-randomization] Position-independent executable (PIE) implements a random base address for the main executable binary and has been in place since April 18, 2004.
[src:application-sandboxing/address-space-layout-randomization] It provides the same address randomness to the main executable as being used for the shared libraries.
[src:application-sandboxing/address-space-layout-randomization] The PIE feature cannot be used together with the prelink feature for the same executable.
[src:application-sandboxing/address-space-layout-randomization] The prelink tool implements randomization at prelink time rather than runtime, because by design prelink aims to handle relocating libraries before the dynamic linker has to, which allows the relocation to occur once for many runs of the program.
[src:application-sandboxing/address-space-layout-randomization] As a result, real address space randomization would defeat the purpose of prelinking.
[src:application-sandboxing/address-space-layout-randomization] In 2014, Marco-Gisbert and Ripoll disclosed *offset2lib* technique that weakens Linux ASLR for PIE executables.
[src:application-sandboxing/address-space-layout-randomization] Linux kernels load PIE executables right after their libraries; as a result, there is a fixed offset between the executable and the library functions.
[src:application-sandboxing/address-space-layout-randomization] If an attacker finds a way to find the address of a function in the executable, the library addresses are also known.
[src:application-sandboxing/address-space-layout-randomization] They demonstrated an attack that finds the address in fewer than 400 tries.
[src:application-sandboxing/address-space-layout-randomization] They proposed a new `randomize_va_space=3` option to randomize the placement of the executable relative to the library, but it is yet to be incorporated into the upstream as of 2024.
[src:application-sandboxing/address-space-layout-randomization] The Linux kernel 5.18 released May 2022 reduced the effectiveness of both 32-bit and 64-bit implementations.
[src:application-sandboxing/address-space-layout-randomization] Linux filesystems call `thp_get_unmapped_area` to respond to a file-backed mmap.
[src:application-sandboxing/address-space-layout-randomization] With a change in 5.18, files greater than 2 MiB are made to return 2 MiB-aligned addresses, so they can be potentially backed by huge pages.
[src:application-sandboxing/address-space-layout-randomization] For 32-bit Linux, many distributions show no randomization *at all* in the placement of the libc.
[src:application-sandboxing/address-space-layout-randomization] For 64-bit Linux, the 28 bits of entropy is reduced to 19 bits.
[src:application-sandboxing/address-space-layout-randomization] In response, Ubuntu has increased its `mmap_rnd_bits` setting.
[src:application-sandboxing/address-space-layout-randomization] Martin Doucha added a Linux Test Project testcase to detect this issue.
[src:application-sandboxing/address-space-layout-randomization] Kernel address space layout randomization (KASLR) enables address space randomization for the Linux kernel image by randomizing where the kernel code is placed at boot time.
[src:application-sandboxing/address-space-layout-randomization] KASLR was merged into the Linux kernel mainline in kernel version 3.14, released on 30 March 2014.
[src:application-sandboxing/address-space-layout-randomization] When compiled in, it can be disabled at boot time by specifying nokaslr as one of the kernel's boot parameters.
[src:application-sandboxing/address-space-layout-randomization] There are several side-channel attacks in x86 processors that could leak kernel addresses.
[src:application-sandboxing/address-space-layout-randomization] In late 2017, kernel page-table isolation (KPTI aka KAISER) was developed to defeat these attacks.
[src:application-sandboxing/address-space-layout-randomization] However, this method cannot protect against side-channel attacks utilizing collisions in branch predictor structures.
[src:application-sandboxing/address-space-layout-randomization] As of 2021, finer grained kernel address space layout randomization (or function granular KASLR, FGKASLR) is a planned extension of KASLR to randomize down to the function level by placing functions in separate sections and reordering them at boot time.
[src:application-sandboxing/address-space-layout-randomization] Microsoft's Windows Vista (released *to manufacturing* November 2006, generally available January 2007) and later have ASLR enabled only for executables and dynamic link libraries that are specifically linked to be ASLR-enabled.
[src:application-sandboxing/address-space-layout-randomization] For compatibility, it is not enabled by default for other applications.
[src:application-sandboxing/address-space-layout-randomization] Typically, only older software is incompatible and ASLR can be fully enabled by editing a registry entry `HKLM\SYSTEM\CurrentControlSet\Control\Session Manager\Memory Management\MoveImages`, or by installing Microsoft's Enhanced Mitigation Experience Toolkit.
[src:application-sandboxing/address-space-layout-randomization] The locations of the heap, stack, Process Environment Block, and Thread Environment Block are also randomized.
[src:application-sandboxing/address-space-layout-randomization] A security whitepaper from Symantec noted that ASLR in 32-bit Windows Vista may not be as robust as expected, and Microsoft has acknowledged a weakness in its implementation.
[src:application-sandboxing/address-space-layout-randomization] Host-based intrusion prevention systems such as *WehnTrust* and *Ozone* also offer ASLR for Windows XP and Windows Server 2003 operating systems.
[src:application-sandboxing/address-space-layout-randomization] Complete details of Ozone's implementation are not available.
[src:application-sandboxing/address-space-layout-randomization] It was noted in February 2012 that ASLR on 32-bit Windows systems prior to Windows 8 can have its effectiveness reduced in low memory situations.
[src:application-sandboxing/address-space-layout-randomization] A similar effect also had been achieved on Linux in the same research.
[src:application-sandboxing/address-space-layout-randomization] The test code caused the Mac OS X 10.7.3 system to kernel panic, so it was left unclear about its ASLR behavior in this scenario.
[src:application-sandboxing/address-space-layout-randomization] Support for ASLR in userland appeared in NetBSD 5.0 (released April 2009), and was enabled by default in NetBSD-current in April 2016.
[src:application-sandboxing/address-space-layout-randomization] Kernel ASLR support on amd64 was added in NetBSD-current in October 2017, making NetBSD the first BSD system to support KASLR.
[src:application-sandboxing/address-space-layout-randomization] In 2003, OpenBSD became the first mainstream operating system to support a strong form of ASLR and to activate it by default.
[src:application-sandboxing/address-space-layout-randomization] OpenBSD completed its ASLR support in 2008 when it added support for PIE binaries.
[src:application-sandboxing/address-space-layout-randomization] OpenBSD 4.4's malloc(3) was designed to improve security by taking advantage of ASLR and gap page features implemented as part of OpenBSD's `mmap` system call, and to detect use-after-free bugs.
[src:application-sandboxing/address-space-layout-randomization] Released in 2013, OpenBSD 5.3 was the first mainstream operating system to enable position-independent executables by default on multiple hardware platforms, and OpenBSD 5.7 activated position-independent static binaries (Static-PIE) by default.
[src:application-sandboxing/address-space-layout-randomization] In Mac OS X Leopard 10.5 (released October 2007), Apple introduced randomization for system libraries.
[src:application-sandboxing/address-space-layout-randomization] In Mac OS X Lion 10.7 (released July 2011), Apple expanded their implementation to cover all applications, stating "address space layout randomization (ASLR) has been improved for all applications.
[src:application-sandboxing/address-space-layout-randomization] As of OS X Mountain Lion 10.8 (released July 2012) and later, the entire system including the kernel as well as kexts and zones are randomly relocated during system boot.
[src:application-sandboxing/address-space-layout-randomization] ASLR has been introduced in Solaris beginning with Solaris 11.1 (released October 2012).
[src:application-sandboxing/address-space-layout-randomization] ASLR in Solaris 11.1 can be set system-wide, per zone, or on a per-binary basis.
[src:application-sandboxing/address-space-layout-randomization] A side-channel attack utilizing branch target buffer was demonstrated to bypass ASLR protection.
[src:application-sandboxing/address-space-layout-randomization] In 2017, an attack named "ASLR⊕Cache" was demonstrated which could defeat ASLR in a web browser using JavaScript.
[src:application-sandboxing/apparmor] In addition to manually creating profiles, AppArmor includes a learning mode, in which profile violations are logged, but not prevented.
[src:application-sandboxing/apparmor] This log can then be used for generating an AppArmor profile, based on the program's typical behavior.
[src:application-sandboxing/apparmor] AppArmor is implemented using the Linux Security Modules (LSM) kernel interface.
[src:application-sandboxing/apparmor] AppArmor is offered in part as an alternative to SELinux, which critics consider difficult for administrators to set up and maintain.
[src:application-sandboxing/apparmor] Unlike SELinux, which is based on applying labels to files, AppArmor works with file paths.
[src:application-sandboxing/apparmor] Proponents of AppArmor claim that it is less complex and easier for the average user to learn than SELinux.
[src:application-sandboxing/apparmor] They also claim that AppArmor requires fewer modifications to work with existing systems.
[src:application-sandboxing/apparmor] For example, SELinux requires a filesystem that supports "security labels", and thus cannot provide access control for files mounted via NFS.
[src:application-sandboxing/apparmor] AppArmor was first used in Immunix Linux 1998–2003.
[src:application-sandboxing/apparmor] At the time, AppArmor was known as SubDomain, a reference to the ability for a security profile for a specific program to be segmented into different domains, which the program can switch between dynamically.
[src:application-sandboxing/apparmor] AppArmor was first made available in SLES and openSUSE and was first enabled by default in SLES 10 and in openSUSE 10.1.
[src:application-sandboxing/apparmor] In May 2005 Novell acquired Immunix and rebranded SubDomain as AppArmor and began code cleaning and rewriting for the inclusion in the Linux kernel.
[src:application-sandboxing/apparmor] From 2005 to September 2007, AppArmor was maintained by Novell.
[src:application-sandboxing/apparmor] SUSE is now the legal owner of the trademarked name AppArmor. openSUSE Tumbleweed transitioned from AppArmor to SELinux for new installation since 11 February 2025, openSUSE Leap 16 switched to SELinux by default as well.
[src:application-sandboxing/apparmor] AppArmor is still available as install-time selection for users who prefer it.
[src:application-sandboxing/apparmor] AppArmor was first successfully ported/packaged for Ubuntu in April 2007.
[src:application-sandboxing/apparmor] AppArmor became a default package starting in Ubuntu 7.10.
[src:application-sandboxing/apparmor] In Ubuntu 8.04 it protected only CUPS by default.
[src:application-sandboxing/apparmor] As of Ubuntu 9.04 more items such as MySQL had installed profiles.
[src:application-sandboxing/apparmor] AppArmor hardening continued to improve in Ubuntu 9.10 with profiles for its guest session, libvirt virtual machines, Evince (document viewer), and an optional Firefox profile.
[src:application-sandboxing/apparmor] AppArmor was integrated into the October 2010, 2.6.36 kernel release.
[src:application-sandboxing/apparmor] AppArmor has been integrated to Synology's DSM since 5.1 Beta in 2014.
[src:application-sandboxing/apparmor] AppArmor was enabled in Solus Release 3 on 2017/8/15.
[src:application-sandboxing/apparmor] AppArmor is enabled by default in Debian 10 (Buster), released in July 2019.
[src:application-sandboxing/apparmor] AppArmor represents one of several possible approaches to the problem of restricting the actions that installed software may take.
[src:application-sandboxing/apparmor] The SELinux system generally takes an approach similar to AppArmor.
[src:application-sandboxing/apparmor] One important difference: SELinux identifies file system objects by inode number instead of path.
[src:application-sandboxing/apparmor] Under AppArmor an inaccessible file may become accessible if a hard link to it is created.
[src:application-sandboxing/apparmor] This difference may be less important than it once was, as Ubuntu 10.10 and later mitigate this with a security module called Yama, which is also used in other distributions.
[src:application-sandboxing/apparmor] SELinux's inode-based model has always inherently denied access through newly created hard links because the hard link would be pointing to an inaccessible inode.
[src:application-sandboxing/apparmor] SELinux and AppArmor also differ significantly in how they are administered and how they integrate into the system.
[src:application-sandboxing/apparmor] Isolation of processes can also be accomplished by mechanisms like virtualization.
[src:application-sandboxing/apparmor] In 2007, the Simplified Mandatory Access Control Kernel was introduced.
[src:application-sandboxing/apparmor] In 2009, a new solution called Tomoyo was included in Linux 2.6.30; like AppArmor, it also uses path-based access control.
[src:application-sandboxing/capability-based-security] A capability-based system, in contrast, is designed with that goal in mind.
[src:application-sandboxing/capability-based-security] Capabilities achieve their objective of improving system security by being used in place of forgeable references.
[src:application-sandboxing/capability-based-security] A forgeable reference (for example, a path name) identifies an object, but does not specify which access rights are appropriate for that object and the user program which holds that reference.
[src:application-sandboxing/capability-based-security] Consequently, any attempt to access the referenced object must be validated by the operating system, based on the ambient authority of the requesting program, typically via the use of an access-control list (ACL).
[src:application-sandboxing/capability-based-security] Instead, in a system with capabilities, the mere fact that a user program possesses that capability entitles it to use the referenced object in accordance with the rights that are specified by that capability.
[src:application-sandboxing/capability-based-security] In theory, a system with capabilities removes the need for any access control list or similar mechanism by giving all entities all and only the capabilities they will actually need.
[src:application-sandboxing/capability-based-security] A capability is typically implemented as a privileged data structure that consists of a section that specifies access rights, and a section that uniquely identifies the object to be accessed.
[src:application-sandboxing/capability-based-security] The user does not access the data structure or object directly, but instead via a handle.
[src:application-sandboxing/capability-based-security] In practice, it is used much like a file descriptor in a traditional operating system (a traditional handle), but to access every object on the system.
[src:application-sandboxing/capability-based-security] Capabilities are typically stored by the operating system in a list, with some mechanism in place to prevent the program from directly modifying the contents of the capability (so as to forge access rights or change the object it points to).
[src:application-sandboxing/capability-based-security] Some systems have also been based on capability-based addressing (hardware support for capabilities), such as Plessey System 250.
[src:application-sandboxing/capability-based-security] Programs possessing capabilities can perform functions on them, such as passing them on to other programs, converting them to a less-privileged version, or deleting them.
[src:application-sandboxing/capability-based-security] The operating system must ensure that only specific operations can occur to the capabilities in the system, in order to maintain the integrity of the security policy.
[src:application-sandboxing/capability-based-security] Capabilities as discussed in this article should not be confused with Portable Operating System Interface (POSIX) 1e/2c "Capabilities".
[src:application-sandboxing/capability-based-security] The latter are coarse-grained privileges that cannot be transferred between processes.
[src:application-sandboxing/capability-based-security] A capability is defined to be a protected object reference which, by virtue of its possession by a user process, grants that process the capability (hence the name) to interact with an object in certain ways.
[src:application-sandboxing/capability-based-security] Those ways might include reading data associated with an object, modifying the object, executing the data in the object as a process, and other conceivable access rights.
[src:application-sandboxing/capability-based-security] The capability logically consists of a reference that uniquely identifies a particular object and a set of one or more of these rights.
[src:application-sandboxing/capability-based-security] Although this identifies a unique object on the system, it does not specify access rights and hence is not a capability.
[src:application-sandboxing/capability-based-security] This pair identifies an object along with a set of access rights.
[src:application-sandboxing/capability-based-security] The pair, however, is still not a capability because the user process's *possession* of these values says nothing about whether that access would actually be legitimate.
[src:application-sandboxing/capability-based-security] The variable `fd` now contains the index of a file descriptor in the process's file descriptor table.
[src:application-sandboxing/capability-based-security] Its existence in the process's file descriptor table is sufficient to show that the process does indeed have legitimate access to the object.
[src:application-sandboxing/capability-based-security] A key feature of this arrangement is that the file descriptor table is in kernel memory and cannot be directly manipulated by the user program.
[src:application-sandboxing/capability-based-security] In traditional operating systems, programs often communicate with each other and with storage using references like those in the first two examples.
[src:application-sandboxing/capability-based-security] Path names are often passed as command-line parameters, sent via sockets, and stored on disk.
[src:application-sandboxing/capability-based-security] These references are not capabilities, and must be validated before they can be used.
[src:application-sandboxing/capability-based-security] In these systems, a central question is "on whose *authority* is a given reference to be evaluated?" This becomes a critical issue especially for processes which must act on behalf of two different authority-bearing entities.
[src:application-sandboxing/capability-based-security] They become susceptible to a programming error known as the confused deputy problem, very frequently resulting in a security hole.
[src:application-sandboxing/capability-based-security] In a capability-based system, the capabilities themselves are passed between processes and storage using a mechanism that is known by the operating system to maintain the integrity of those capabilities.
[src:application-sandboxing/capability-based-security] One novel approach to solving this problem involves the use of an orthogonally persistent operating system.
[src:application-sandboxing/capability-based-security] In such a system, there is no need for entities to be discarded and their capabilities be invalidated, and hence require an ACL-like mechanism to restore those capabilities at a later time.
[src:application-sandboxing/capability-based-security] The operating system maintains the integrity and security of the capabilities contained within all storage, both volatile and nonvolatile, at all times; in part by performing all serialization tasks by itself, rather than requiring user programs to do so, as is the case in most operating systems.
[src:application-sandboxing/capability-based-security] Because user programs are relieved of this responsibility, there is no need to trust them to reproduce only legal capabilities, nor to validate requests for access using an access control mechanism.
[src:application-sandboxing/capability-based-security] An example implementation is the Flex machine from the early 1980s.
[src:application-sandboxing/capability-based-security] Portable Operating System Interface (POSIX) draft 1003.1e specifies a concept of permissions called "capabilities".
[src:application-sandboxing/capability-based-security] However, POSIX capabilities differ from capabilities in this article.
[src:application-sandboxing/capability-based-security] A POSIX capability is not associated with any object; a process having CAP_NET_BIND_SERVICE capability can listen on any TCP port under 1024.
[src:application-sandboxing/capability-based-security] In contrast, Capsicum Unix hybridizes a true capability-system model with a Unix design and POSIX API.
[src:application-sandboxing/capability-based-security] Capsicum capabilities are a refined form of file descriptor, a delegable right between processes and additional object types beyond classic POSIX, such as processes, can be referenced via capabilities.
[src:application-sandboxing/capability-based-security] In Capsicum capability mode, processes are unable to utilize global namespaces (such as the filesystem namespace) to look up objects, and must instead inherit or be delegated them.
[src:application-sandboxing/capability-based-security] This system is found natively in FreeBSD, but patches are available to other systems.
[src:application-sandboxing/sandbox-software-development] The concept of sandboxing is built into revision control software such as Git, CVS and Subversion (SVN), in which developers "check out" a *copy* of the source code tree, or a branch thereof, to examine and work on.
[src:application-sandboxing/sandbox-software-development] After the developer has fully tested the code changes in their own sandbox, the changes would be checked back into and merged with the repository and thereby made available to other developers or end users of the software.
[src:application-sandboxing/sandbox-software-development] Sandboxing (see also 'soft launching') is often considered a best practice when making any changes to a system, regardless of whether that change is considered 'development', a modification of configuration state, or updating the system.
[src:application-sandboxing/sandbox-software-development] The term sandbox is commonly used for the development of web services to refer to a mirrored production environment for use by external developers.
[src:application-sandboxing/sandbox-software-development] Typically, a third-party developer will develop and create an application that will use a web service from the sandbox, which is used to allow a third-party team to validate their code before migrating it to the production environment.
[src:application-sandboxing/sandbox-software-development] Microsoft, Google, Amazon, Salesforce, PayPal, eBay, and Yahoo, among others, provide such services.
[src:application-sandboxing/sandbox-software-development] Wikis also typically employ a shared sandbox model of testing, though it is intended principally for learning and outright experimentation with features rather than for testing of alterations to existing content (the wiki analog of source code).
[src:application-sandboxing/sandbox-software-development] An edit preview mode is usually used instead to test specific changes made to the texts or layout of wiki pages.
[src:application-sandboxing/seccomp] seccomp mode is enabled via the `prctl(2)` system call using the `PR_SET_SECCOMP` argument, or (since Linux kernel 3.17) via the `seccomp(2)` system call. seccomp mode used to be enabled by writing to a file, `/proc/self/seccomp`, but this method was removed in favor of `prctl()`.
[src:application-sandboxing/seccomp] In some kernel versions, seccomp disables the `RDTSC` x86 instruction, which returns the number of elapsed processor cycles since power-on, used for high-precision timing.
[src:application-sandboxing/seccomp] Some consider seccomp comparable to OpenBSD pledge(2) and FreeBSD capsicum(4).
[src:application-sandboxing/seccomp] seccomp was first devised by Andrea Arcangeli in January 2005 for use in public grid computing and was originally intended as a means of safely running untrusted compute-bound programs.
[src:application-sandboxing/seccomp] It was merged into the Linux kernel mainline in kernel version 2.6.12, which was released on March 8, 2005.
[src:application-sandboxing/security-enhanced-linux] SELinux is a set of kernel modifications and user-space tools that have been added to various Linux distributions.
[src:application-sandboxing/security-enhanced-linux] Its architecture strives to separate enforcement of security decisions from the security policy, and streamlines the amount of software involved with security policy enforcement.
[src:application-sandboxing/security-enhanced-linux] The key concepts underlying SELinux can be traced to several earlier projects by the United States National Security Agency (NSA).
[src:application-sandboxing/security-enhanced-linux] A Linux kernel integrating SELinux enforces mandatory access control policies that confine user programs and system services, as well as access to files and network resources.
[src:application-sandboxing/security-enhanced-linux] Limiting privilege to the minimum required to work reduces or eliminates the ability of these programs and daemons to cause harm if faulty or compromised (for example via buffer overflows or misconfigurations).
[src:application-sandboxing/security-enhanced-linux] This confinement mechanism operates independently of the traditional Linux (discretionary) access control mechanisms.
[src:application-sandboxing/security-enhanced-linux] It has no concept of a "root" superuser, and does not share the well-known shortcomings of the traditional Linux security mechanisms, such as a dependence on setuid/setgid binaries.
[src:application-sandboxing/security-enhanced-linux] The security of an "unmodified" Linux system (a system without SELinux) depends on the correctness of the kernel, of all the privileged applications, and of each of their configurations.
[src:application-sandboxing/security-enhanced-linux] A fault in any one of these areas may allow the compromise of the entire system.
[src:application-sandboxing/security-enhanced-linux] In contrast, the security of a "modified" system (based on an SELinux kernel) depends primarily on the correctness of the kernel and its security-policy configuration.
[src:application-sandboxing/security-enhanced-linux] While problems with the correctness or configuration of applications may allow the limited compromise of individual user programs and system daemons, they do not necessarily pose a threat to the security of other user programs and system daemons or to the security of the system as a whole.
[src:application-sandboxing/security-enhanced-linux] From a purist perspective, SELinux provides a hybrid of concepts and capabilities drawn from mandatory access controls, mandatory integrity controls, role-based access control (RBAC), and type enforcement architecture.
[src:application-sandboxing/security-enhanced-linux] Third-party tools enable one to build a variety of security policies.
[src:application-sandboxing/security-enhanced-linux] SELinux was designed to demonstrate the value of mandatory access controls to the Linux community and how such controls could be added to Linux.
[src:application-sandboxing/security-enhanced-linux] Originally, the patches that make up SELinux had to be explicitly applied to the Linux kernel source; SELinux was merged into the Linux kernel mainline in the 2.6 series of the Linux kernel.
[src:application-sandboxing/security-enhanced-linux] The NSA, the original primary developer of SELinux, released the first version to the open source development community under the GNU GPL on 22 December 2000.
[src:application-sandboxing/security-enhanced-linux] The software was merged into the mainline Linux kernel 2.6.0-test3, released on 8 August 2003.
[src:application-sandboxing/security-enhanced-linux] Other significant contributors include Red Hat, Network Associates, Secure Computing Corporation, Tresys Technology, and Trusted Computer Solutions.
[src:application-sandboxing/security-enhanced-linux] Experimental ports of the FLASK/TE implementation have been made available via the TrustedBSD Project for the FreeBSD and Darwin operating systems.
[src:application-sandboxing/security-enhanced-linux] Security-Enhanced Linux implements the Flux Advanced Security Kernel (FLASK).
[src:application-sandboxing/security-enhanced-linux] Such a kernel contains architectural components prototyped in the Fluke operating system.
[src:application-sandboxing/security-enhanced-linux] These provide general support for enforcing many kinds of mandatory access control policies, including those based on the concepts of type enforcement, role-based access control, and multilevel security.
[src:application-sandboxing/security-enhanced-linux] FLASK, in turn, was based on DTOS, a Mach-derived Distributed Trusted Operating System developed as a part of earlier research in mandatory access control systems.
[src:application-sandboxing/security-enhanced-linux] A comprehensive list of the original and external contributors to SELinux was hosted at the NSA website until maintenance ceased sometime in 2009.
[src:application-sandboxing/security-enhanced-linux] The following list reproduces the original as preserved by the Internet Archive Wayback Machine.
[src:application-sandboxing/security-enhanced-linux] The scope of their contributions was listed in the page and has been omitted for brevity, but it can be accessed through the archived copy.
[src:application-sandboxing/security-enhanced-linux] SELinux users and roles do not have to be related to the actual system users and roles.
[src:application-sandboxing/security-enhanced-linux] For every current user or process, SELinux assigns a three string context consisting of a username, role, and domain (or type).
[src:application-sandboxing/security-enhanced-linux] This system is more flexible than normally required: as a rule, most of the real users share the same SELinux username, and all access control is managed through the third tag, the domain.
[src:application-sandboxing/security-enhanced-linux] The circumstances under which a process is allowed into a certain domain must be configured in the policies.
[src:application-sandboxing/security-enhanced-linux] The command `runcon` allows for the launching of a process into an explicitly specified context (user, role, and domain), but SELinux may deny the transition if it is not approved by the policy.
[src:application-sandboxing/security-enhanced-linux] Files, network ports, and other hardware also have an SELinux context, consisting of a name, role (seldom used), and type.
[src:application-sandboxing/security-enhanced-linux] In the case of file systems, mapping between files and the security contexts is called labeling.
[src:application-sandboxing/security-enhanced-linux] The labeling is defined in policy files but can also be manually adjusted without changing the policies.
[src:application-sandboxing/security-enhanced-linux] Hardware types are quite detailed, for instance, `bin_t` (all files in the folder /bin) or `postgresql_port_t` (PostgreSQL port, 5432).
[src:application-sandboxing/security-enhanced-linux] The SELinux context for a remote file system can be specified explicitly at mount time.
[src:application-sandboxing/security-enhanced-linux] SELinux adds the `-Z` switch to the shell commands `ls`, `ps`, and some others, allowing the security context of the files or process to be seen.
[src:application-sandboxing/security-enhanced-linux] Typical policy rules consist of explicit permissions, for example, which domains the user must possess to perform certain actions with the given target (read, execute, or, in case of network port, bind or connect), and so on.
[src:application-sandboxing/security-enhanced-linux] More complex mappings are also possible, involving roles and security levels.
[src:application-sandboxing/security-enhanced-linux] A typical policy consists of a mapping (labeling) file, a rule file, and an interface file, that define the domain transition.
[src:application-sandboxing/security-enhanced-linux] These three files must be compiled together with the SELinux tools to produce a single policy file.
[src:application-sandboxing/security-enhanced-linux] The resulting policy file can be loaded into the kernel to make it active.
[src:application-sandboxing/security-enhanced-linux] Loading and unloading policies does not require a reboot.
[src:application-sandboxing/security-enhanced-linux] The policy files are either hand written or can be generated from the more user friendly SELinux management tool.
[src:application-sandboxing/security-enhanced-linux] They are normally tested in permissive mode first, where violations are logged but allowed.
[src:application-sandboxing/security-enhanced-linux] The `audit2allow` tool can be used later to produce additional rules that extend the policy to allow all legitimate activities of the application being confined.
[src:application-sandboxing/security-enhanced-linux] SELinux has been implemented in Android since version 4.3.
[src:application-sandboxing/security-enhanced-linux] Among free community-supported Linux distributions, Fedora was one of the earliest adopters, including support for it by default since Fedora Core 2.
[src:application-sandboxing/security-enhanced-linux] Other distributions include support for it such as Debian as of version 9 Stretch release and Ubuntu as of 8.04 Hardy Heron.
[src:application-sandboxing/security-enhanced-linux] As of version 11.1, openSUSE contains SELinux "basic enablement".
[src:application-sandboxing/security-enhanced-linux] SUSE Linux Enterprise (SLE) 11 features SELinux as a "technology preview".
[src:application-sandboxing/security-enhanced-linux] SELinux is popular in systems based on Linux containers, such as CoreOS Container Linux and rkt.
[src:application-sandboxing/security-enhanced-linux] It is useful as an additional security control to help further enforce isolation between deployed containers and their host.
[src:application-sandboxing/security-enhanced-linux] SELinux is available since 2005 as part of Red Hat Enterprise Linux (RHEL) version 4 and all future releases.
[src:application-sandboxing/security-enhanced-linux] This presence is also reflected in corresponding versions of derived systems such as CentOS, Scientific Linux, AlmaLinux and Rocky Linux.
[src:application-sandboxing/security-enhanced-linux] The supported policy in RHEL4 is targeted policy which aims for maximum ease of use and thus is not as restrictive as it might be.
[src:application-sandboxing/security-enhanced-linux] Future versions of RHEL are planned to have more targets in the targeted policy which will mean more restrictive policies.
[src:application-sandboxing/security-enhanced-linux] RHEL version 5 introduced multilevel security (MLS) policy for servers only.
[src:application-sandboxing/security-enhanced-linux] Fedora Linux 10 introduced a minimum policy, designed for certain platforms such as low-memory devices and virtual machines.
[src:application-sandboxing/security-enhanced-linux] openSUSE Tumbleweed transitioned from AppArmor to SELinux for new installation since 11 February 2025, and SLE/openSUSE Leap 16 was shipped with SELinux by default as well. openSUSE/SLE adopted RHEL/Fedora policies for its SELinux implementation although with some differences.
[src:application-sandboxing/security-enhanced-linux] AppArmor is retained for existing Tumbleweed and SLE/openSUSE Leap 15.x installation (users can manually migrate their existing installation to SELinux).
[src:application-sandboxing/security-enhanced-linux] AppArmor is also available as an install-time selection for Tumbleweed users, but not on SLE/Leap 16.
[src:application-sandboxing/security-enhanced-linux] SELinux can potentially control which activities a system allows each user, process, and daemon, with very precise specifications.
[src:application-sandboxing/security-enhanced-linux] It is used to confine daemons such as database engines or web servers that have clearly defined data access and activity rights.
[src:application-sandboxing/security-enhanced-linux] This limits potential harm from a confined daemon that becomes compromised.
[src:application-sandboxing/security-enhanced-linux] SELinux represents one of several possible approaches to the problem of restricting the actions that installed software can take.
[src:application-sandboxing/security-enhanced-linux] Another popular alternative is called AppArmor and is available on SUSE Linux Enterprise Server (SLES), openSUSE, and Debian-based platforms.
[src:application-sandboxing/security-enhanced-linux] AppArmor was developed as a component to the now-defunct Immunix Linux platform.
[src:application-sandboxing/security-enhanced-linux] Because AppArmor and SELinux differ radically from one another, they form distinct alternatives for software control.
[src:application-sandboxing/security-enhanced-linux] Whereas SELinux re-invents certain concepts to provide access to a more expressive set of policy choices, AppArmor was designed to be simple by extending the same administrative semantics used for DAC up to the mandatory access control level.
[src:application-sandboxing/security-enhanced-linux] Isolation of processes can also be accomplished by mechanisms such as virtualization.
[src:application-sandboxing/security-enhanced-linux] The NSA has adopted some of the SELinux concepts in Security-Enhanced Android.
[src:application-sandboxing/security-enhanced-linux] General Dynamics builds and distributes PitBull Trusted Operating System, a multilevel security (MLS) enhancement for Red Hat Enterprise Linux.
[src:application-sandboxing/security-enhanced-linux] Multi-Category Security (MCS) is an enhancement to SELinux for Red Hat Enterprise Linux that allows users to label files with categories, in order to further restrict access through discretionary access control and type enforcement.
[src:application-sandboxing/security-enhanced-linux] Categories provide additional compartments within sensitivity levels used by multilevel security (MLS).
